    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Previous names",
            "shortText": "<p><i>Gibbula articulata, Minolia articulata</i></p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_9_10369",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Small, lustreless shell, colour white with small brown and blackish patches near apex and weaker brown bands towards aperture, height 0.75 to 1.1 times diameter. Each whorl bears 3-5 angular spiral ridges and is crossed by numerous weak, diagonal, scratch-like axial lines. Ventrally the umbilicus is large and open. Operculum a flat, transparent disc containing spiral growth lines.</p><p>Living animal transparent white to yellowish-white with opaque white patches. Cephalic tentacles long and banded in black and white. When fully extended the lateral margin of the foot has several pairs of long epipodial tentacles. Eye stalks moderately long and prominent. Left neck lobe a series of branching tentacles and right one a rolled tube that serves as an exhalent siphon.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_10370",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Shell diameter up to 8 mm, height variable 6–9 mm.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_10371",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Endemic to South Africa.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> False Bay to KwaZulu-Natal (incorrect distribution map in publication listed below), 5–140 m.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_10372",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Found among sediments on shallow reefs and can bury itself rapidly in the sediment and burrow efficiently. Exhibits a twisting and leaping response, or foot-thrashing, if approached by predators such as starfish, predatory whelks or crabs. The radula is unusually thin and delicate in this genus. Little else known about biology.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_10341",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": [
                {
                    "text": "",
                    "altText": "",
                    "title": "",
                    "imageUrl": {
                        "1x": "/localcosmos/user_content/content_images/image-3182-250.webp",
